    <!-- Common Mistakes -->
    <section id="common-mistakes" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">1. Assuming Real Estate Qualifies Automatically</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            Simply buying property doesn't qualify for investor visa. The investment must be "productive"—generating
            income or creating jobs. Real estate only qualifies as part of a tourism business (hotel, vacation rentals
            with management company) or commercial development.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">2. Underestimating Processing Times</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            Official estimates are 3-6 months, but delays are common. Plan for 6-12 months. Don't make irreversible
            decisions (selling home country property, ending employment) until you have approval in hand.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">3. Skipping CAJA Enrollment</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            CAJA enrollment is mandatory for all residents, regardless of private insurance. Non-compliance can
            jeopardize residency renewal. Enroll within 3 months of approval even if you have comprehensive
            international coverage.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">4. Using Non-Apostilled Documents</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            All foreign documents must be apostilled (for Hague Convention countries) or legalized by Costa Rican
            consulate, then translated by an official Costa Rican translator. Documents older than 6 months (especially
            police clearances) will be rejected.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">5. Not Working with a Local Attorney</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            Costa Rica's bureaucracy requires local expertise. An immigration attorney familiar with investor visas
            can navigate the process, ensure documents are properly formatted, and communicate with immigration
            officials on your behalf. Budget $1,500-$3,000 for legal fees.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

