    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faqs" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work in Costa Rica with an investor visa?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Yes, investor residents can work in Costa Rica, including managing their investment business. Unlike some
            residency categories (Rentista, Pensionado), investor visa holders have full work authorization. You can
            also establish additional businesses beyond your qualifying investment.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can apply for citizenship?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Standard path is 7 years of legal residency (5 years for citizens of Spain and most Latin American
            countries). You must maintain residency status throughout, demonstrate basic Spanish proficiency, pass
            a civics test, and show integration into Costa Rican society. Dual citizenship is permitted.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if my investment fails?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            If your qualifying investment loses value or the business fails, you may not be able to renew your
            residency. You'd need to either reinvest to meet the $150,000 threshold or transition to a different
            residency category (Rentista if you have passive income, Pensionado if you have pension). Consult an
            immigration attorney if your investment situation changes.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I have to live in Costa Rica full-time?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            You must visit Costa Rica at least once every 2 years to maintain residency. However, to progress toward
            permanent residency (after 3 years) and citizenship (after 7 years), you need to demonstrate actual
            residence—spending most of your time in the country. Frequent extended absences could affect naturalization eligibility.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I include family members in my application?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Yes, your spouse and dependent children (under 25 if in school) can be included as dependents. Each
            dependent adds to the paperwork but doesn't require additional investment. Adult children and parents
            need separate applications with their own qualifying income or investment.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Costa Rica a good tax jurisdiction for investors?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Costa Rica has a territorial tax system but is transitioning toward worldwide taxation. Currently, only
            Costa Rican-source income is taxed (15-25% personal income tax). However, new rules are expanding what
            constitutes "local source" income. It's not a tax haven—consult a tax professional familiar with both
            Costa Rican and your home country tax law.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
        <p class="text-primary-900 mb-4">
          Costa Rica's investor visa is ideal for those seeking a balanced lifestyle in a stable, democratic country
          with excellent healthcare and natural beauty. The $150,000 investment requirement is mid-range globally, but
          the mandate for "productive" investment means this isn't a passive real estate play—you need genuine
